# Chapter 3 – Core Architecture: The Project Graph

---

# 1. Introduction

The most important architectural decision in Project Sarthi is that the application does **not** think in terms of files.

Instead, it thinks in terms of relationships.

Traditional development tools primarily expose a file system.

Project Sarthi exposes a **Project Graph**.

The Project Graph is the internal representation of everything the platform understands about a software project.

Every parser contributes information to this graph.

Every visualization reads from this graph.

Every future analysis engine operates on this graph.

The graph becomes the single source of truth for the entire application.

---

# 2. What is the Project Graph?

The Project Graph is a directed graph containing:

* Nodes (entities inside the project)
* Edges (relationships between those entities)

Example:

Authentication Module

↓

POST /login

↓

Login Controller

↓

Auth Service

↓

User Model

↓

Database

↓

Frontend Login Page

↓

Documentation

Notice that this is not a folder hierarchy.

It is a representation of how the software actually behaves.

---

# 3. Design Goals

The Project Graph must satisfy the following requirements.

## Single Source of Truth

Every entity exists exactly once.

If the same route appears in multiple visualizations, those visualizations reference the same underlying node.

---

## Framework Independent

The graph must not depend on Express, Next.js or Prisma.

Instead, parsers translate framework-specific information into a common graph model.

This allows future plugins to emit identical graph structures regardless of language or framework.

---

## Extensible

New parsers should only need to create nodes and edges.

They should never modify existing graph logic.

---

## Queryable

The graph should answer questions efficiently.

Examples:

* Which frontend pages use this API?
* Which modules depend on Redis?
* Which documentation references this service?
* Which routes use JWT middleware?

The graph exists primarily to answer questions.

---

# 4. Node Types

Version 1 of Project Sarthi supports the following node categories.

## Project

Represents the entire software project.

Contains metadata such as:

* Name
* Repository URL
* Framework
* Language
* Last Analysis
* Parser Version

There will only be one Project node.

---

## Module

The highest logical grouping.

Examples:

Authentication

Payments

Inventory

Orders

Users

Analytics

Modules become the primary navigation units.

Modules are detected using route-based grouping.

---

## Route

Represents an API endpoint.

Example:

POST /login

GET /users

PATCH /orders/:id

Stores:

HTTP Method

Path

Controller

Validation

Middleware

Response Type

---

## Controller

Represents request handlers.

Controllers connect incoming requests with business logic.

---

## Service

Contains business logic.

Services usually communicate with:

* Database
* External APIs
* Other services

---

## Database Model

Represents:

Prisma models

Mongoose schemas

Stores:

Fields

Relationships

Indexes (future)

---

## Frontend Component

Represents React or Next.js components that consume APIs.

Initially only API-consuming pages/components will be included.

---

## Documentation

Represents Markdown documents.

Examples:

README

API Documentation

Architecture Notes

Feature Documentation

---

## External Service

Represents third-party systems.

Examples:

Stripe

Cloudinary

Firebase

OpenAI (future)

Redis

SMTP

---

## Environment Variable

Represents required configuration values.

Examples:

DATABASE_URL

JWT_SECRET

SENDGRID_API_KEY

---

# 5. Edge Types

Nodes become valuable because of their relationships.

Version 1 supports the following edge types.

Module

contains

Route

Route

handled_by

Controller

Controller

uses

Service

Service

queries

Database Model

Service

calls

External Service

Frontend Component

calls

Route

Documentation

describes

Module

Documentation

describes

Route

Environment Variable

required_by

Service

Module

depends_on

Module

Future edge types can be added without changing the graph architecture.

---

# 6. Why Route-Based Module Detection?

This decision deserves explanation.

Software projects can be grouped in many ways.

Folder structure.

Database models.

Imports.

Dependency clustering.

Project Sarthi intentionally chooses **route-based module detection**.

Reason:

Routes are usually the clearest representation of software features.

Example:

/auth/login

/auth/register

/auth/refresh

These naturally belong to the Authentication module.

Likewise:

/orders

/orders/:id

/orders/history

belong to the Orders module.

This grouping closely matches how developers mentally organize applications.

If multiple folders contribute to one route group, they are still considered part of the same logical module.

Future versions may allow additional grouping strategies through plugins.

---

# 7. Graph Construction Pipeline

The graph is built incrementally.

Step 1

Clone repository.

↓

Step 2

Detect technologies.

↓

Step 3

Select compatible parsers.

↓

Step 4

Parse project files.

↓

Step 5

Extract entities.

↓

Step 6

Create graph nodes.

↓

Step 7

Create graph edges.

↓

Step 8

Run graph validation.

↓

Step 9

Run analysis engine.

↓

Step 10

Persist graph to database.

No visualization begins until the graph has been successfully constructed.

---

# 8. Graph Validation

Before storing the Project Graph, Sarthi performs validation.

Validation ensures:

No duplicate nodes.

No invalid references.

No orphan edges.

All relationships reference existing entities.

Every route belongs to exactly one module.

Every controller references valid services.

Validation failures are logged for debugging.

---

# 9. Graph Persistence

The graph should be stored separately from the original repository.

Reason:

The graph represents understanding.

The repository represents source code.

Keeping them separate allows future graph versions without modifying repository data.

The database stores:

Nodes

Edges

Metadata

Analysis Results

Project Statistics

Future AI Embeddings (Version 2)

---

# 10. Graph Versioning

Every analysis produces a graph version.

Reasons:

Track architectural evolution.

Compare analyses.

Support future diff visualizations.

Recover previous project states.

Version 1 will store graph versions but will not expose comparison tools.

This keeps future expansion possible without increasing MVP complexity.

---

# 11. What the Graph Enables

The Project Graph is the foundation for every major feature.

Project Overview

Reads project metadata.

Module Explorer

Reads Module nodes.

Dependency Graph

Visualizes graph edges.

Request Flow Explorer

Traverses Route → Controller → Service chains.

Project Health

Runs graph analysis.

Search

Queries graph nodes.

Resume Session

Compares current graph against previous analysis.

Future AI

Receives graph context instead of raw source code.

Every feature becomes another way of interacting with the same underlying data.

---

# 12. Engineering Principles

The Project Graph should never contain presentation logic.

It should describe software only.

Visualizations are responsible for deciding how information is displayed.

Parsers are responsible for extracting information.

Analysis engines are responsible for generating insights.

The graph itself remains a clean, framework-independent representation of the software.

Maintaining this separation of responsibilities is essential for long-term scalability.

