# Project Sarthi - Technical Design Document

## Chapter 6 – Database Design & Data Model

---

### 1. Introduction

The database is responsible for storing **understanding**, not source code.

The GitHub repository remains the source of truth for the software itself.

Project Sarthi stores:

* Information extracted from the repository.
* The generated Project Graph.
* Analysis results.
* Historical graph versions.
* User accounts.
* Project metadata.

This separation is intentional.

If a repository is deleted from the database and imported again, Sarthi should be capable of reconstructing the same understanding from the repository.

---

### 2. Why PostgreSQL?

Project Sarthi requires a database capable of handling:

* Highly relational data.
* Complex queries.
* Version history.
* Fast filtering.
* Reliable transactions.

PostgreSQL satisfies all these requirements while remaining one of the most widely used production databases.

Advantages:

* Excellent relational capabilities.
* Mature ecosystem.
* Strong Prisma support.
* Free and open source.
* Resume value.
* Easy deployment later.

Version 1 intentionally avoids graph databases such as Neo4j.

Although the Project Graph is conceptually a graph, PostgreSQL can represent it efficiently for our current scale.

If future requirements justify a dedicated graph database, only the persistence layer should change—not the architecture.

---

### 3. Why Prisma?

Prisma is selected as the ORM because it provides:

* Type-safe database access.
* Automatic TypeScript types.
* Database migrations.
* Schema-first development.
* Excellent developer experience.
* Strong PostgreSQL integration.

Since the frontend and backend are written in TypeScript, Prisma integrates naturally with the project.

---

### 4. First-Time Setup

Since this project is also intended to expand technical skills, PostgreSQL and Prisma are considered learning objectives.

Version 1 development assumes no previous experience.

Before backend implementation begins, complete the following setup.

#### Install PostgreSQL

Install the latest stable PostgreSQL release.

During installation:

* Remember the password for the `postgres` user.
* Keep the default port (5432).
* Install pgAdmin.

After installation verify:

* PostgreSQL service is running.
* pgAdmin opens successfully.
* You can create a new database.

---

#### Install Prisma

Inside the backend project:

```bash
npm install prisma --save-dev
npm install @prisma/client
```

Initialize Prisma:

```bash
npx prisma init
```

This generates:

```text
backend/

├── prisma/
│   └── schema.prisma
│
├── .env
```

The `.env` file stores the PostgreSQL connection string.

---

#### Verify Connection

Create a database named:

```text
project_sarthi
```

Update:

```env
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://..."
```

Run:

```bash
npx prisma migrate dev
```

Successful migration confirms the setup.

---

### 5. Data Ownership

Every piece of stored information belongs to one of four categories.

#### User Data

Authentication.

Preferences.

Owned projects.

---

#### Project Data

Repository.

Metadata.

Framework information.

Repository settings.

---

#### Graph Data

Nodes.

Edges.

Relationships.

Versions.

---

#### Analysis Data

Insights.

Warnings.

Health metrics.

Generated summaries.

Keeping these concerns separate simplifies future development.

---

### 6. High-Level Database Structure

```text
Users
│
├── Projects
│     │
│     ├── Graph Versions
│     │      │
│     │      ├── Nodes
│     │      └── Edges
│     │
│     ├── Analyses
│     ├── Insights
│     └── Health Reports
```

Everything ultimately belongs to a Project.

---

### 7. Core Tables

Version 1 requires the following tables.

---

#### User

Purpose:

Authentication.

Stores:

* ID
* Name
* Email
* Password Hash
* Created At
* Updated At

Future:

Profile settings.

Theme.

Notification preferences.

---

#### Project

Represents one software repository.

Stores:

* ID
* Owner
* Name
* Description
* GitHub URL
* Default Branch
* Framework
* Language
* Last Analysis
* Current Graph Version
* Created At

One user may own many projects.

---

#### GraphVersion

Every successful repository analysis creates one Graph Version.

Stores:

* Version Number
* Analysis Timestamp
* Git Commit Hash
* Repository Branch
* Parser Version

Purpose:

Allow comparison between analyses.

Support Resume Session.

Support future graph history.

---

#### Node

Stores every Project Graph node.

Fields include:

* ID
* Graph Version
* Node Type
* Name
* Metadata (JSON)
* Created At

Examples:

Authentication Module.

POST /login.

User Model.

Auth Service.

README.

The metadata field stores type-specific information.

Example:

Route metadata:

* HTTP Method
* Path

Model metadata:

* Collection Name
* Fields

Documentation metadata:

* File Path

---

#### Edge

Stores relationships between nodes.

Fields:

* Source Node
* Destination Node
* Relationship Type

Examples:

Authentication

contains

POST /login

Route

handled_by

Controller

Controller

uses

Service

Service

queries

Database Model

The Edge table forms the backbone of the Project Graph.

---

#### Analysis

Represents one completed analysis.

Stores:

* Analysis Duration
* Parser Version
* Status
* Graph Version
* Summary

This table exists independently from GraphVersion because future analyses may include additional processing stages.

---

#### Insight

Stores every generated insight.

Fields:

* Title
* Description
* Severity
* Related Node
* Related Module
* Analysis
* Created At

Examples:

Authentication documentation is outdated.

Orders module has high coupling.

Unused middleware detected.

---

#### HealthMetric

Stores health indicators.

Each metric is independent.

Examples:

Documentation Coverage

Circular Dependencies

Unused Routes

Dependency Complexity

Future versions can introduce new metrics without modifying existing data.

---

### 8. Why Separate Nodes and Metadata?

Different node types require different information.

Example:

A Route stores:

* HTTP Method
* URL
* Response Type

A Database Model stores:

* Fields
* Relationships

A Markdown document stores:

* File Path
* Heading Structure

Instead of creating separate tables for every node type, Version 1 stores common information in the Node table and node-specific information inside a JSON metadata column.

Advantages:

* Flexible.
* Easy plugin support.
* Easier migrations.
* Simpler graph construction.

---

### 9. Graph Versioning Strategy

Every repository analysis creates a completely new graph version.

Old versions remain unchanged.

Advantages:

Reliable history.

Future comparisons.

Rollback support.

Cleaner implementation.

Version 1 stores graph history but only exposes the latest graph in the interface.

---

### 10. Indexing Strategy

To maintain performance, PostgreSQL indexes should be added for:

* Project ID
* Graph Version
* Node Type
* Relationship Type
* Analysis Timestamp
* User ID

These indexes will significantly improve graph traversal and search performance.

---

### 11. Why Not Store Source Code?

Project Sarthi is not a backup service.

The repository already stores source code.

Duplicating source files inside PostgreSQL would:

Increase storage.

Complicate synchronization.

Create unnecessary inconsistencies.

Instead, only derived knowledge is stored.

---

### 12. Data Flow

```text
GitHub Repository
        │
        ▼
Clone Repository
        │
        ▼
Parser Engine
        │
        ▼
Graph Builder
        │
        ▼
Project Graph
        │
        ▼
Analysis Engine
        │
        ▼
PostgreSQL
        │
        ├── Projects
        ├── Nodes
        ├── Edges
        ├── Analyses
        ├── Insights
        └── Health Metrics
```

The database becomes the persistent memory of Project Sarthi.

---

### 13. Backup & Recovery

Version 1 assumes GitHub is the authoritative source.

If database information is lost:

* Repository is cloned again.
* Parsers rebuild the Project Graph.
* Analysis Engine regenerates insights.

This design intentionally minimizes irreversible data loss.

---

### 14. Future Expansion

The current schema allows future additions without redesign.

Potential additions include:

* AI embeddings.
* Team collaboration.
* Comments.
* Saved graph layouts.
* User annotations.
* Runtime logs.
* Deployment history.

These features can be attached to existing tables rather than replacing them.

---

### 15. Engineering Principles

The database should persist knowledge rather than implementation.

Every stored entity should answer one question:

"Will storing this make the project easier to understand later?"

If the answer is no, it likely does not belong in the database.

The schema should remain stable even as parser plugins, frontend technologies, and supported frameworks continue to evolve.

