The search experience should feel more like navigating knowledge than searching files.

---

### 12. Analysis Progress

Repository analysis may take several seconds.

Instead of displaying a loading spinner, the frontend should present progress.

Stages include:

Repository Cloning.

Technology Detection.

Parser Execution.

Graph Construction.

Analysis.

Saving Results.

Completed.

Users should always understand what the system is currently doing.

---

### 13. Error Handling

Errors should provide useful information without exposing internal implementation.

Examples:

Repository inaccessible.

Authentication expired.

Unsupported framework detected.

Parser partially completed.

Graph generation failed.

Each error should include a recommended next action whenever possible.

---

### 14. Responsive Design

Version 1 prioritizes desktop usage.

Tablet support should remain functional.

Mobile support is limited to viewing projects.

Graph exploration is not optimized for mobile during the MVP.

---

### 15. UI Principles

Every screen should satisfy three requirements.

Immediately communicate purpose.

Minimize unnecessary clicks.

Preserve user context.

Whenever possible, navigation should occur within the current page rather than through repeated page transitions.

---

### 16. Design Decisions

#### DD-001

Avoid dashboard overload.

The Overview page should summarize the project rather than becoming a collection of unrelated widgets.

---

#### DD-002

Prefer progressive disclosure.

Show high-level information first.

Reveal details only when users request them.

---

#### DD-003

Visualizations should explain relationships.

Graphs exist to improve understanding.

Decorative graphics have no place in Project Sarthi.

---

#### DD-004

Every major feature should be reachable within two clicks from the Overview page.

This reduces navigation friction.

---

### 17. Engineering Principles

The frontend should never perform project analysis.

It presents data.

The backend understands data.

Maintaining this separation keeps the application predictable, testable and scalable.

Whenever frontend logic begins making engineering decisions about the project, that logic likely belongs in the Analysis Engine instead.

