# Project Sarthi - Technical Design Document

## Chapter 9 – Graph Visualization & User Interaction

---

### 1. Introduction

The Project Graph is the defining visual feature of Project Sarthi.

However, its purpose is not to display every relationship inside a software project.

Its purpose is to improve understanding.

Every design decision in the graph visualization should answer one question:

**"Will this help the developer understand the project faster?"**

If the answer is no, the information probably does not belong in the graph.

---

### 2. Visualization Philosophy

Software projects naturally contain hundreds or even thousands of relationships.

Displaying everything simultaneously creates visual noise rather than understanding.

Project Sarthi intentionally reveals information progressively.

Users begin with a simplified view.

Additional information appears only when requested.

Understanding should increase as the user explores.

---

### 3. Why React Flow?

React Flow provides the capabilities required without forcing us to build a graph engine ourselves.

It gives us:

* Interactive nodes
* Custom node components
* Zoom and pan
* Minimap
* Edge rendering
* Keyboard shortcuts
* Smooth animations
* Node selection
* Layout flexibility

Project Sarthi focuses on understanding software, not reinventing graph rendering.

---

### 4. Graph Modes

The same Project Graph should support multiple perspectives.

The underlying data never changes.

Only the visualization changes.

---

#### Mode 1 – Module View (Default)

This is the first graph every user sees.

Each node represents a logical module.

Example:

```text
Authentication

Orders

Inventory

Payments

Analytics

Notifications
```

Edges represent dependencies between modules.

Purpose:

Provide a high-level understanding of the project architecture.

This mode intentionally hides implementation details.

---

#### Mode 2 – Request Flow View

Focused on one endpoint.

Example:

```text
POST /login

↓

Validation

↓

JWT Middleware

↓

Login Controller

↓

Auth Service

↓

User Model

↓

Database
```

Purpose:

Understand how requests travel through the application.

---

#### Mode 3 – Dependency View

Displays relationships between technical components.

Examples:

Services

Database Models

External APIs

Middleware

Controllers

Purpose:

Understand coupling and dependencies.

---

#### Mode 4 – Documentation View

Shows how documentation relates to implementation.

Examples:

README

Architecture Notes

API Documentation

Module Documentation

Purpose:

Identify undocumented or outdated areas.

---

### 5. Node Types

Every node should communicate its purpose immediately.

Version 1 includes:

Module

Route

Controller

Service

Database Model

Frontend Component

Documentation

External Service

Environment Variable

Every node type should have a consistent visual identity.

---

### 6. Node Design

Every node should contain only essential information.

Example:

Route Node

```
POST

/login
```

Module Node

```
Authentication

12 Routes

4 Services
```

Service Node

```
AuthService
```

The graph should remain readable even at medium zoom levels.

---

### 7. Edge Design

Edges represent relationships.

Examples:

contains

handled_by

uses

queries

calls

depends_on

describes

Edges should remain subtle.

Nodes communicate primary information.

Edges communicate relationships.

---

### 8. Layout Strategy

Automatic layout is required.

Users should never manually arrange graphs.

Version 1 should use a layered layout algorithm.

High-level structure:

```text
Modules

↓

Routes

↓

Controllers

↓

Services

↓

Database
```

This immediately communicates architectural flow.

Future versions may allow users to switch layouts.

---

### 9. Progressive Disclosure

The graph should never display everything initially.

Instead:

Overview

↓

Expand Module

↓

Expand Route

↓

Expand Controller

↓

Expand Service

Every expansion reveals one additional level of detail.

This dramatically reduces visual clutter.

---

### 10. Interaction Model

Every interaction should answer a question.

Selecting a node should never simply highlight it.

Instead it should update the Context Panel.

Possible interactions:

Single Click

Select node.

Double Click

Expand node.

Mouse Hover

Quick preview.

Right Click (future)

Additional actions.

Keyboard Shortcuts

Navigation.

---

### 11. Context Panel

The Context Panel appears on the right side of the interface.

It changes depending on the selected node.

Example:

Authentication Module

Displays:

Overview

Routes

Dependencies

Documentation

Related Insights

Recent Changes

Health Indicators

Navigation Links

The graph and panel together create the complete exploration experience.

---

### 12. Graph Filtering

Users should be able to reduce complexity.

Available filters:

Hide Documentation

Hide Environment Variables

Hide External Services

Show Only API Flow

Show Only Database

Show Only Frontend

Filtering changes visibility only.

The Project Graph itself never changes.

---

### 13. Highlighting

Highlighting should communicate relationships.

Example:

Selecting

AuthService

automatically highlights:

Connected Routes

Connected Controllers

Connected Models

Dependent Modules

Everything else becomes visually subdued.

This guides attention naturally.

---

### 14. Navigation

The graph should never trap users.

Breadcrumbs should always indicate their current position.

Example:

```
Project

>

Authentication

>

POST /login

>

AuthService
```

Users should always know where they are.

---

### 15. Search Integration

Searching for an entity should automatically:

Locate the node.

Center the graph.

Highlight relationships.

Open the Context Panel.

Search and graph exploration should feel like one continuous experience.

---

### 16. Health Visualization

Health indicators should integrate naturally into the graph.

Examples:

Documentation Issue

Small warning badge.

Circular Dependency

Highlighted relationship.

Unused Route

Subtle indicator.

Large Module

Additional information in Context Panel.

The graph should never become a wall of warning icons.

---

### 17. Analysis Progress Visualization

While analysis runs, users should see progress.

Example:

```
Repository

✓

Technology Detection

✓

Parser Execution

✓

Graph Construction

...

Analysis

Waiting

Saving

Waiting
```

This provides confidence that the system is actively working.

---

### 18. Animations

Animations should communicate change.

Examples:

Node expansion.

Graph transitions.

Selection.

Filtering.

Analysis completion.

Animations should remain subtle.

Avoid decorative effects.

---

### 19. Accessibility

Version 1 should consider accessibility from the beginning.

Requirements:

Keyboard navigation.

Screen reader labels.

High contrast compatibility.

Color should never be the only method of conveying information.

Icons and labels should reinforce meaning.

---

### 20. Design Decisions

#### DD-005

The graph should visualize understanding rather than source code.

---

#### DD-006

Every interaction should reduce cognitive load.

---

#### DD-007

Progressive disclosure is preferred over displaying every relationship simultaneously.

---

#### DD-008

Context Panels are preferred over opening new pages because they preserve exploration context.

---

### 21. Engineering Principles

The Project Graph should feel like exploring a city rather than reading a spreadsheet.

Users begin with neighborhoods (modules).

They gradually explore streets (routes).

Eventually they inspect individual buildings (services, controllers and models).

At every level, the interface should communicate structure, relationships and purpose.

When a user leaves the graph, they should understand the software better than when they entered—not because they saw more information, but because they saw the right information in the right order.

